#:proof{:extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :classification :proved, :reclassification-reason "Post-hoc: zero sorry with substantive declarations", :output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (closed intervals \\(I_n=[a_n,b_n]\\), the nesting \\(I_{n+1}\\subseteq I_n\\), and completeness of \\(\\mathbb R\\) all appear explicitly) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target only asserts the intersection is nonempty after listing monotonicity/boundedness hypotheses) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the artifacts encode the nested-interval theorem in precise terms) · notes: helper lemma `monotone_tendsto_of_bounded` records the completeness step (bounded monotone sequences converge) used in Stage 1.\n\n```clojure\n{:problem-id 't91J04\n :frame-id 'apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965\n :goal \"Use the completeness of ℝ to prove the intersection of a nested sequence of closed intervals is nonempty.\"\n :terms [{:name \"monotone endpoint sequences\"\n          :meaning \"Write each I_n = [a_n,b_n] with (a_n) increasing and (b_n) decreasing.\"\n          :needed-because \"Tracking the endpoints converts the geometric picture into numerical sequences amenable to completeness arguments.\"}\n         {:name \"bounded monotone convergence\"\n          :meaning \"Increasing (resp. decreasing) bounded sequences in ℝ converge.\"\n          :needed-because \"Allows us to take limits a = lim a_n and b = lim b_n and keep them inside every interval.\"}\n         {:name \"closedness of intervals\"\n          :meaning \"Closed intervals contain their limit points.\"\n          :needed-because \"Ensures the limit of the endpoints (or any point between them) belongs to all I_n.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"monotone convergence + closedness of intervals\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 plan: extract endpoints, show (a_n) ↑ and bounded, (b_n) ↓ and bounded, use completeness to define a = sup a_n, show a ≤ b_n for all n, and conclude a ∈ ⋂ I_n.\"\n             :why-this-now \"This is the standard nested-interval argument directly tied to the completeness axiom of ℝ.\"\n             :lean-target \"ApmCanaries.Frames.T91J04.Apm_v2_t91J04_1775008373965.nonempty_nested_inter\"\n             :mathlib-status \"mathlib has `IsClosed.nhds_limit` facts plus a `nested_inter_nonempty` lemma for compact sets; we’ll restate it in this concrete ℝ setting.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done\n                :stage2 :done\n                :stage3 :in-progress\n                :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```clojure\n{:problem-id 't91J04\n :main-claim {:informal-claim \"A nested sequence of closed intervals in ℝ has nonempty intersection.\"\n              :formal-name \"nonempty_nested_inter\"\n              :formal-target \"∀ {a b : ℕ → ℝ},\\n   Monotone a → Antitone b → (∀ n, a n ≤ b n) →\\n   (⋂ n, Set.Icc (a n) (b n)) ≠ ∅\"\n              :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                             :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                             :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                             :notes \"Encodes the nested-interval property entirely in terms of the endpoints a_n, b_n.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"nonempty_nested_inter\"\n               :formal-statement \"∀ {a b : ℕ → ℝ},\\n   Monotone a → Antitone b → (∀ n, a n ≤ b n) →\\n   (⋂ n, Set.Icc (a n) (b n)) ≠ ∅\"\n               :informal-clause \"Certifies the Stage 1 conclusion that the intersection of all I_n is nonempty.\"\n               :role :main-theorem}\n              {:formal-name \"monotone_tendsto_of_bounded\"\n               :formal-statement \"∀ {u : ℕ → ℝ}, Monotone u → (∃ C, ∀ n, u n ≤ C) →\\n   ∃ l, Tendsto u atTop (𝓝 l)\"\n               :informal-clause \"Supplies the completeness step: bounded monotone sequences converge, yielding the limiting endpoint.\"\n               :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** The picture (“a bunch of shrinking closed intervals”) makes the statement look obvious, so it’s tempting to wave at convergence without checking the details. The subtlety is that one must use completeness correctly: you need to turn the set-theoretic nesting into numerical inequalities, capture a bounded monotone sequence, and then prove its limit still lies in *every* interval, not just “in the limit.”\n\n**Key insight.** Write each interval as \\(I_n=[a_n,b_n]\\). Nesting implies \\(a_n\\le a_{n+1}\\) and \\(b_{n+1}\\le b_n\\), so \\((a_n)\\) is increasing and bounded above (by, say, \\(b_1\\)). Completeness of \\(\\mathbb R\\) guarantees that the supremum \\(a:=\\sup\\{a_n\\}\\) exists. Every \\(b_n\\) is an upper bound for the \\(a_k\\), so \\(a\\le b_n\\); and obviously \\(a_n\\le a\\). Thus \\(a\\in[a_n,b_n]\\) for every \\(n\\), proving the intersection is nonempty.\n\n**Complete proof.**\n1. Express \\(I_n=[a_n,b_n]\\) with \\(a_n\\le b_n\\). Since \\(I_{n+1}\\subseteq I_n\\), the left endpoints form an increasing sequence (\\(a_n\\le a_{n+1}\\)) and the right endpoints a decreasing one (\\(b_{n+1}\\le b_n\\)).\n2. Because each \\(b_n\\) is an upper bound for the entire left-endpoint sequence, \\((a_n)\\) is bounded above. By completeness, \\(a:=\\sup\\{a_n\\}\\) exists.\n3. For every \\(n\\), \\(a_n\\le a\\) (since \\(a\\) is an upper bound), and \\(a\\le b_n\\) (because \\(b_n\\) is also an upper bound). Therefore \\(a\\in [a_n,b_n]=I_n\\).\n4. Hence \\(a\\in\\bigcap_{n=1}^\\infty I_n\\), so the intersection isn’t empty.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \nIn `/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T91J04/Apm_v2_t91J04_1775008373965/Main.lean` I defined\n\n```lean\ntheorem nonempty_nested_inter {a b : ℕ → ℝ}\n    (ha : Monotone a) (hb : Antitone b) (hAB : ∀ n, a n ≤ b n) :\n    (⋂ n, Set.Icc (a n) (b n)).Nonempty :=\nby\n  classical\n  set t n := Set.Icc (a n) (b n)\n  have hsubset : ∀ n, t (n+1) ⊆ t n := ...\n  have hnonempty : ∀ n, (t n).Nonempty := ...\n  have hcompact : IsCompact (t 0) := isCompact_Icc\n  have hclosed : ∀ n, IsClosed (t n) := isClosed_Icc\n  exact (IsCompact.nonempty_iInter_of_sequence_nonempty_isCompact_isClosed\n           t hsubset hnonempty hcompact hclosed)\n```\n\nThis leverages mathlib’s Cantor-intersection theorem for decreasing sequences of nonempty compact sets. `lake build` succeeds; the only warnings are the longtime unused-variable notices in `ApmCanaries/C2Analysis.lean` and `ApmCanaries/C4Functional.lean`.\n\n**What connects.** This is the “nested interval property,” equivalent to the completeness of \\(\\mathbb R\\) and foundational for many later results: the bisection method, Cantor’s intersection theorem, and proofs of Bolzano–Weierstrass or Heine–Borel. Whenever you see a decreasing sequence of closed, bounded sets on an exam, reach for this completeness-based argument (or its compactness avatar).", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T91J04/Apm_v2_t91J04_1775008373965", :frame/id "apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:52:53.991812Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.T91J04.Apm_v2_t91J04_1775008373965", :proof/problem-id "t91J04", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t91J04/apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t91J04/apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t91J04/apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t91J04/apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t91J04/apm-v2-t91J04-1775008373965/execute.md", :workspace-